# Application environment
# Copy this file to ".env" and adjust values for your environment.

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Mock-only demo (no DB / APIs)
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Minimal template: copy env.mock.example to .env (or set APP_MODE=mock only).
# Local: scripts/run_mock.ps1 or scripts/run_mock.sh
# Docker (single container, port 8050): docker compose -f docker-compose.mock.yml up -d --build

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Dash app mode (UI)
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Leave unset or set to microservice for normal API-backed mode.
# Set to "mock" for demo UI with static data (Analytics + DAA + full DC mock datasets).
# Docker (profile): docker compose --profile mock up -d  (service app-mock, port 8051)
# APP_MODE=mock
#
# Optional sidebar / tab title for customer demos (default: Datalake WebUI)
# APP_BRAND_TITLE=Datalake WebUI

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# PostgreSQL (required by API services)
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Point to your real database. Docker Compose API containers load this file via
# env_file — use a hostname/IP reachable from inside the container (not "localhost"
# for a DB on the host; use host.docker.internal or the host LAN IP on Windows/macOS).
# Use your real DB host (never commit secrets to git).
DB_HOST=your-db-host
DB_PORT=5000
DB_NAME=datalake
DB_USER=datalakeui
DB_PASS=changeme

# Optional: external SLA API (leave empty to disable SLA fetches)
# SLA_API_KEY=

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Docker Compose — microservice profile (Redis + 3 APIs + Dash; external DB above)
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Uncomment to activate the microservice profile by default (see docker-compose.yml):
# COMPOSE_PROFILES=microservice
#
# When the Dash app runs inside Compose, it calls APIs by service name (same network).
# You can override these if needed:
# DATACENTER_API_URL=http://datacenter-api:8000
# CUSTOMER_API_URL=http://customer-api:8000
# QUERY_API_URL=http://query-api:8000
#
# Optional: revision label for the Dash container (build + runtime). Shown bottom-right in the UI.
# Example: export APP_BUILD_ID=$(git rev-parse --short HEAD) before docker compose build app
# APP_BUILD_ID=dev

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Optional: local PostgreSQL in Docker (profile "with-db" only — not microservice)
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# If you run: docker compose --profile with-db up -d
# then point APIs at the Compose db service:
# DB_HOST=db
# DB_PORT=5432
# DB_NAME=datalake
# DB_USER=datalakeui
# DB_PASS=change_me

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AuraNotify (Dash app — Availability tabs; X-API-Key header)
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Base URL of the AuraNotify API (no trailing slash).
# AURANOTIFY_BASE_URL=http://10.0.0.1:5001
# Preferred key name:
# AURANOTIFY_API_KEY=
# Legacy/alternate name (also supported by the client):
# ANOTIFY_API_KEY=
